{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}

The '''Guinean Democratic Movement''' ({{lang-pt|Movimento Democrático Guineense}}) is a [[political party]] in [[Guinea-Bissau]].

==History==
The party was established on 14 February 2003 and was led by [[Silvestre Alves]].<ref>Bogdan Szajkowski (2005) ''Political Parties of the World'', p272</ref> In the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]] it received 0.98% of the vote, failing to win a seat in the [[National People's Assembly (Guinea-Bissau)|National People's Assembly]]. The [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2008|2008 elections]] saw the party's vote share fall to just 0.14%, again failing to win a seat.<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p278</ref> 

Alves openly condemned the increasingly repressive actions of the Military Command following the [[2012 Guinea-Bissau coup d'état|2012 military coup]], and in October 2012 was arrested and severely beaten, requiring intensive care in hospital.<ref>Mendy, p279</ref> The party's application to contest the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 2014|2014 general elections]] was rejected by the Supreme Court.<ref>[http://www.anacao.cv/online/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4420:guine-bissau-supremo-chumba-oito-candidaturas-presidenciais-e-sete-partidos&catid=87:destaque&Itemid=475 GUINÉ-BISSAU: SUPREMO “CHUMBA” OITO CANDIDATURAS PRESIDENCIAIS E SETE PARTIDOS] A Nação, 16 March 2014</ref>

