'''Michel Adama-Tamboux''' (December 3, 1928 – March 18, 2018) was a [[Central African Republic|Central African]] politician and diplomat. He was a [[List of Presidents of the National Assembly of the Central African Republic|President of the National Assembly of the Central African Republic]] from 1960 to 1966.<ref name="LaNouvelleCentrafrique">{{cite news|title=Centrafrique : DÉPÊCHE/Nécrologie : Décès de Michel ADAMA-TAMBOUX|url=http://www.lanouvellecentrafrique.info/2018/03/19/centrafrique-depeche-necrologie-deces-de-michel-adama-tamboux/|work=La Nouvelle Centrafrique|date=March 2018}}</ref> He was incarcerated by [[Jean-Bédel Bokassa]] from 1966 to 1970, and served as the ambassador to the United Nations and Egypt in the 1970s.<ref name="LaNouvelleCentrafrique"/>

He was a member of the political party [[Movement for the Social Evolution of Black Africa|MESAN]].

